body:
In this issue I want to request a new feature. The existing implementation although not supported but must be flagged as a bug. 

Verilator issues warnings for **shortreal** usage and **$shortrealtobits**. Ultimately they are promoted to **real** and **$realtobits** respectively. I have added a simple test case that demonstrates use of the **shortreal** type, including conversion and display operations. It highlights current Verilator limitations related to FP32 handling.
```
module test();

    shortreal float32;

    initial begin

       float32 = shortreal'(2.3);

       $display("The floating point number is %0e", float32);
       $display("The floating point number in hex is  %h", $shortrealtobits(float32));

       $finish;
    end

endmodule
```

When I verilate this test then get these warnings.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a5531d06-b5b5-4871-8738-c5821cd05653)

Checked it against the official documenation from here: [https://verilator.org/guide/latest/warnings.html#cmdoption-arg-SHORTREAL](https://verilator.org/guide/latest/warnings.html#cmdoption-arg-SHORTREAL) that it is not supported. The reason behind it is very vague that "shortreal is not widely supported across industry tools" . This is arguement is not valid. The **shortreal** type (IEEE-754 32-bit floating-point) is frequently used in hardware simulation and development. 


My solver verilator: z3
My verilator verison: Verilator 5.035 devel rev v5.034-27-g258becd17. It's a git master verison.
My OS and distrbution details: Ubuntu 24.04.2 LTS

LRM: IEEE Standard for SystemVerilog—Unified Hardware Design, Specification, and Verification Language

